{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2011}} {{ infobox person | name = Iachim Sergheevici Grosul | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1912|09|21}} | birth_place = Cărăgaş, [[Administrative Region of Slobozia|Slobozia county]] | death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1976|09|28|1912|09|21}} | death_place = [[Chişinău]] | body_discovered = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} --> | residence = | nationality = | ethnicity = | citizenship = | other_names = | known_for = }}
'''Iachim Sergheevici Grosul''' (name also rendered as '''Yakim Grosul''') (21 September 1912 – 28 September 1976) was a [[Moldovans|Moldovan]] scientist, and the first president of the Academy of Science of the [[Moldavian SSR]] in the [[Soviet Union]].
== Biography ==
He was born in the village of Cărăgaş, [[Administrative Region of Slobozia|Slobozia county]]. In 1937, he graduated from the Pedagogic Institute in [[Tiraspol]]. After this, he worked at the Institute as lecturer in history. He joined the [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union|Communist Party]] in 1939. In 1940 he became dean of the History Department. From 1947, he was vice director, and from 1954, he was president of the Moldavian section of the [[Russian Academy of Sciences#History|USSR Academy of Sciences]].<ref name="Grosul1">Grosul, Iachim S. (1974) ''Akademija nauk Moldavskoj SSR'' Academy of Sciences of the Moldavian Soviet Socialist Republic, Kišinev, [http://worldcat.org/oclc/71567689 OCLC 71567689], in Russian</ref> In 1961, he was elected as the first president of the new [[Academy of Sciences of Moldova|Academy of Science of the Moldavian Soviet Socialist Republic]].<ref name="Grosul1"/> He was a good organiser, scientist and historian. Grosul developed and edited the ''Enciclopedia Republici Sovietice Socialiste Moldoveneşti'', an eight-volume encyclopedia published between 1964 and 1981. He is noted for his book on the economic development of [[Bessarabia]] under Russian rule in the 19th century. However, his works relating to history, were many times censured, a common practice in the marxist dogmatic Soviet Union.
In 2004, his image and name were used on a silver coin minted by [[Transnistrian Republican Bank|Central Bank of Transnistria]] to honor this native of what today is [[Transnistria]], as part of a series of memorable coins called "[[The Outstanding People of Pridnestrovie]]".<ref>[http://www.jewellernet.com/info/news/lenta/2004_12_28_17_22_55.html "Silver memorial coins are issued in Pridnestrovye" (28 December 2004) ''Russian Jewellery Network'']</ref>
