[[File:MLKStreet.JPG|thumb|300px|Martin Luther King Jr. Street at [[Liberty Bell Park]] in Jerusalem.]] [[File:Martin Luther King Jr. Memorial, San Francisco.jpg|thumb|300px|The Martin Luther King Jr. Memorial in [[Yerba Buena Gardens]].]]
This is a list of memorials to [[Martin Luther King Jr]].
== United States == There are numerous memorials to King in the United States, including:
* [[Martin Luther King Jr. Memorial]] on the [[National Mall]] in Washington, D.C.<ref>{{cite web|title=Washington, DC Martin Luther King Jr. National Memorial Project Foundation Breaks Ground On Historic $100 Million Memorial On The National Mall In Washington, D.C.|date=November 6, 2006|accessdate=August 27, 2008|publisher=Washington, DC Martin Luther King Jr. National Memorial Project Foundation|url=http://www.mlkmemorial.org/site/apps/nlnet/content2.aspx?c=hkIUL9MVJxE&b=1601407&ct=3612187|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616170228/http://www.mlkmemorial.org/site/apps/nlnet/content2.aspx?c=hkIUL9MVJxE&b=1601407&ct=3612187|archivedate=June 16, 2012}} </ref> King was the first African American and the fourth non-president honored with his own memorial in the National Mall area.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celebrating the Birthday of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.|publisher=U.S. Department of State|last=Tobias|first=Randall L.|url=https://www.state.gov/f/releases/remarks2007/87649.htm|date=January 18, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071115141138/https://www.state.gov/f/releases/remarks2007/87649.htm|archivedate=November 15, 2007|accessdate=January 16, 2012}} </ref> In 1996, Congress authorized the [[Alpha Phi Alpha]] fraternity, of which King is still a member, to establish a foundation to manage fundraising and design of a national memorial to King. The memorial opened in August 2011<ref>{{cite news|title=A Dream Fulfilled, Martin Luther King Memorial Opens |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/23/us/23mlk.html?_r=1&smid=fb-nytimes&WT.mc_id=US-SM-E-FB-SM-LIN-ADF-082311-NYT-NA&WT.mc_ev=click |work=New York Times |date=August 23, 2011 |first=Sabrina |last=Tavernise |archivedate=January 4, 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6DQEaTSBT?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/23/us/23mlk.html?_r=2&smid=fb-nytimes&WT.mc_id=US-SM-E-FB-SM-LIN-ADF-082311-NYT-NA&WT.mc_ev=click& |deadurl=no |df= }} </ref> and is administered by the [[National Park Service]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/mlkm/index.htm |title=Martin Luther King Jr. Memorial |publisher=National Park Service |accessdate=January 4, 2013 |archivedate=January 4, 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6DQPYa1Eo?url=http://www.nps.gov/mlkm/index.htm |deadurl=no |df=mdy }}</ref> The address of the monument, 1964 [[Independence Avenue (Washington, D.C.)|Independence Avenue, SW]], commemorates the year that the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]] became law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonlife.com/2011/07/26/fyidc-paying-tribute-to-dr-king/|title=FYIDC: Paying Tribute To Dr. King|author=Guevara, Brittni|date=July 26, 2011|work=Washington Life|accessdate=January 20, 2013}}</ref> * The ''[[Landmark for Peace Memorial]]'' in [[Indianapolis, Indiana]]<ref name="wp 20110804">{{cite * More than 730 cities in the United States have [[Streets named after Martin Luther King Jr.|streets named after King]].</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://personal.ecu.edu/aldermand/pubs/alderman_chapter.pdf|last=Alderman|first=Derek H.|title=Naming Streets for Martin Luther King Jr.: No Easy Road|work=Landscape and Race in the United States|publisher=Routledge Press|date=February 13, 2006|accessdate=July 4, 2011}}{{dead link|date=September 2013}} </ref> * [[King County, Washington]], rededicated its name in his honor in 1986 and changed its logo to an image of his face in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title=King County Was Rededicated For MLK|work=The Seattle Times|accessdate=June 13, 2008|date=January 18, 1998|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19980118&slug=2729257}} See also: {{cite web|title=New logo is an image of civil rights leader|publisher=King County|url=http://www.kingcounty.gov/operations/logo.aspx|accessdate=June 13, 2008}}</ref> * The city government center in [[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania]], is named in honor of King.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. Essay Competition Winners Announced|publisher=City of Harrisburg|url=http://www.harrisburgpa.gov/pressReleases/prArchives/2003/01/20030119_mlkEssay.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071207045944/http://www.harrisburgpa.gov/pressReleases/prArchives/2003/01/20030119_mlkEssay.html|archivedate=December 7, 2007|date=January 19, 2003|accessdate=August 27, 2008}}</ref> * In 1980, the U.S. [[Department of the Interior]] designated King's boyhood home in Atlanta and several nearby buildings the [[Martin Luther King Jr. National Historic Site]].<ref name="wp 20110804"/> * A [[Martin Luther King Jr. (Wilson)|bust of Dr. King]] was added to the "gallery of notables" in the [[United States Capitol]] in 1986, portraying him in a "restful, nonspeaking pose."<ref name=artworkd>{{cite news|last=Trescott|first=Jacqueline|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/across-dc-statues-honor-african-americans/2011/07/28/gIQA5f1iZJ_story.html|title=Across D.C., statues honor African Americans|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=2011-08-23|accessdate=January 19, 2012}}</ref> * The beginning words of King's "[[I Have a Dream]]" speech are etched on the steps of the [[Lincoln Memorial]], at the place where King stood during that speech.<ref name="etched">Ramanathan, Levanya, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/gog/best-bets/artifacts-black-history,100680.html "Pieces of Black History"], ''Washington Post'', January 27, 2012. Retrieved January 27, 2012.</ref> These words from the speech—"five short lines of text carved into the granite on the steps of the Lincoln Memorial"—were etched in 2003, on the 40th anniversary of the march to Washington, by stone carver Andy Del Gallo, after a law was passed by Congress providing authorization for the inscription.<ref>name="etched"/news|last=Wax|first=Emily|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/martin-luther-king-jr-sites-across-the-globe/2011/08/04/gIQAK4R9YJ_story.html|title=Martin Luther King Jr. sites across the globe|series=Lifestyle: Full Coverage: The Martin Luther King Jr. Memorial|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=August 23, 2011|accessdate=October 20, 2011}}</ref> * The ''[[Homage to King]]'' sculpture in [[Atlanta, Georgia]]<ref name="wp 20110804"/> * [[The Dream (sculpture)|''The Dream'' sculpture]] in [[Portland, Oregon]] * The [[Martin Luther King Jr. Memorial Bridge]] in [[Fort Wayne, Indiana]] * The [[National Civil Rights Museum]], at the Lorraine Motel in [[Memphis, Tennessee]], where King died<ref name="wp 20110804"/> * [[Brown Chapel A.M.E. Church (Selma, Alabama)|Brown Chapel A.M.E. Church]] in [[Selma, Alabama]]<ref name="wp 20110804"/> * On October 11, 2015, the ''Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' reported a proposed "Freedom Bell" may be installed atop [[Stone Mountain]] honoring King and his "I Have a Dream" speech, specifically the line "Let freedom ring from Stone Mountain of Georgia."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2015/10/11/a-monument-to-mlk-will-crown-stone-mountain/|title=A monument to MLK will crown Stone Mountain&nbsp;– Political Insider blog|publisher=}}</ref> * A [[bust of Martin Luther King Jr. (Alston)|bust of Martin Luther King Jr.]] has been in the collection of the collection of the [[Smithsonian Institution]]'s [[National Portrait Gallery (United States)|National Portrait Gallery]] since 1974, and displayed in the [[White House]] since 2000; a second cast is in the collection of the [[National Museum of African American History and Culture]].
== Internationally == Numerous other memorials honor him around the world, including: * The Reverend Martin Luther King Jr. Church in [[Debrecen, Hungary]]<ref name="wp 20110804"/> * The King-Luthuli Transformation Center in [[Johannesburg, South Africa]]<ref name="wp 20110804"/> * The Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. Forest in [[Israel]]'s Southern Galilee region (along with the [[Coretta Scott King]] Forest in Biriya Forest, Israel)<ref name="wp 20110804"/> * The Martin Luther King Jr. School in [[Accra, Ghana]]<ref name="wp 20110804"/> * The Gandhi-King Plaza (garden), at the India International Center in [[New Delhi]], India * In [[Norfolk, Virginia]] stands a memorial in honor of King. The 83-foot-high granite [[obelisk]] was conceived by former Norfolk Councilman and General District Court Judge [[Joseph A. Jordan Jr.]]<ref>[http://www.downtownnorfolk.org/go/martin-luther-king-jr-memorial "Martin Luther King Jr. Memorial"]. Downtown Norfolk. Retrieved February 20, 2016.</ref><ref>Parker, Stacy (February 1, 2012). [http://pilotonline.com/guides/african-american-today/memorial-s-story-reflects-king-s-vision/article_f447b59b-b20e-53b8-9ab6-4d3124640fb4.html "Memorial's story reflects King's vision"]. ''[[The Virginian Pilot]]''.</ref>
